      "content": [
        {
          "type": "title",
          "value": "Existence and Possession"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "To say you 'have' something or that something 'exists', use <strong>有</strong> (jau5). The negative form is <strong>冇</strong> (mou5), which means 'not have' or 'not exist'."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "有",
          "romanization": "jau5",
          "translation": "Have / Exist"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "冇",
          "romanization": "mou5",
          "translation": "Not have / Not exist"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "冇貓",
          "romanization": "mou5 maau1",
          "translation": "Not have a cat"
        },
        {
          "type": "title",
          "value": "Asking Questions: jau5 mou5"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Just like the 'A-not-A' structure you learned earlier, you can ask if someone has something by saying <strong>有無</strong> (jau5 mou5)."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "你有無書呀？",
          "romanization": "nei5 jau5 mou5 syu1 aa3?",
          "translation": "Do you have any books?"
        }
      ]
    },
